  "prompt": "What is the diffusion of water through a membrane?",
  "response": "Osmosis is the diffusion of water through a semipermeable membrane from an area of higher water concentration (lower solute concentration) to an area of lower water concentration (higher solute concentration). Key characteristics include:\n\n1. Characteristics:\n- Water molecules move across a semipermeable membrane\n- Movement occurs from areas of lower solute concentration to higher solute concentration\n- Driven by concentration gradient\n- Requires no energy expenditure\n\n2. Types of solutions:\n- Hypotonic: Lower solute concentration\n- Hypertonic: Higher solute concentration\n- Isotonic: Equal solute concentrations\n\n3. Membrane properties:\n- Allows water molecules to pass through\n- Blocks larger solute molecules\n- Maintains selective permeability\n\n4. Importance:\n- Crucial in biological systems\n- Regulates water balance in cells\n- Maintains cell volume\n- Essential for nutrient transport\n- Supports physiological processes\n\n5. Examples:\n- Water movement in plant cells\n- Kidney filtration\n- Cell hydration\n- Blood fluid balance\n\nOsmosis is a fundamental process in living systems that helps maintain cellular homeostasis and supports various biological functions.",
